The 'National Park Service' ('NPS') is the U.S. federal agency that manages all
national parks, many national monuments, and other conservation and historical
properties with various title designations. It was created on August
25, 1916, by Congress through the National Park Service Organic Act.

It is an agency of the United States Department of the Interior. Most of the
direct management of the NPS is delegated by the Secretary of the Interior to
the National Park Service Director, who must be confirmed by the Senate.

The 21,989 employees of the NPS oversee units, of which 59 are designated
national parks. Budget Justifications and Performance Information, Fiscal
